			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>World War II-era navigation system shut down<br />
By Mike M. Ahlers, CNN<br />
February 8, 2010 9:25 p.m. EST</p>
<p>Coast Guard Loran Station Attu in Alaska is one of five that will remain open until June.</p>
<p>STORY HIGHLIGHTS<br />
U.S. shut down 19 of 24 land-based Loran-C navigation stations on Monday<br />
Administration says Loran no longer needed in era of Global Positioning System<br />
Critics warn GPS is vulnerable to cyber-attacks, suggest keeping Loran as backup<br />
Washington &#8212; Good night, Loran.<br />
In a series of small ceremonies, the U.S. Coast Guard on Monday shut down Loran-C, a navigation and timing system that has guided mariners and aviators since World War II.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2010/TECH/02/08/loran.navigation.shutdown/index.html">Read more</a> at CNN.com</p>
]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://flyingpilot.com/?feed=rss2&amp;p=93</wfw:commentRss>
